Cutaneous fibromas are frequently occurring neoplasms naturally occurring virus of white-tailed deer (Odocoileus virginianus). Deer fibromas appear on the skin as hard and round tumors that can be as big as 1 cm in diameter. The tumors are blackish or brown and have a rough textured surface. They do not cause the animal harm unless clumps of fibromas interfere with breathing, eating, or walking. "Fibromas have been reported in white-tailed deer (Odocoileus virginianus), mule deer (Odocoileus hemionus), black-tailed deer (Odocoileus hemionus), fallow deer (Cervus dama), red deer (Cervus elaphus), roe deer (Capreolus capreolus), Sika deer (Cervus nippon), moose (Alces alces) and caribou (Rangifer caribou)." Other common names for fibromas are deer warts or Shopeâ€™s warts/fibroma. They are found across the entirety of the whitetail's range.
